To solve for $x$, we want to isolate $x$ on one side of the equation. 

First, we can start by multiplying both sides by $x+1$ to get rid of the denominator: 

\begin{align*}
\frac{x-9}{x+1} &= 2 \\
\frac{x-9}{x+1} \cdot (x+1) &= 2 \cdot (x+1) \\
x-9 &= 2x+2 \\
\end{align*}

Next, we can simplify by subtracting $x$ from both sides: 

\begin{align*}
x-9 &= 2x+2 \\
x-2x &= 9+2 \\
-x &= 11 \\
\end{align*}

Finally, we can solve for $x$ by multiplying both sides by $-1$: 

\begin{align*}
-x &= 11 \\
(-1) \cdot (-x) &= (-1) \cdot 11 \\
x &= -11 \\
\end{align*}

Therefore, the solution to the equation is $x=-11$.

