Let $x$ be the length of each leg of the isosceles right triangle. Since the triangle is isosceles, the altitude to the hypotenuse splits the triangle into two congruent right triangles. Therefore, each of these right triangles has legs of length $x$ and hypotenuse of length $x\sqrt{2}$. Using the formula for the area of a triangle, we have:

\begin{align*}
\text{Area of triangle} &= \frac{1}{2}(\text{base})(\text{height}) \\
&= \frac{1}{2}(x)(x) \\
&= \frac{1}{2}x^2
\end{align*}

We can also use the fact that the area of a triangle can be expressed as $\frac{1}{2}(\text{base})(\text{height})$ in a different way. Since the altitude to the hypotenuse has length $6$, it splits the hypotenuse into two segments, each of length $x/2$. Therefore, the base of the triangle is $x$, and the height is $6$. Using this formula for the area of a triangle, we have:

\begin{align*}
\text{Area of triangle} &= \frac{1}{2}(\text{base})(\text{height}) \\
&= \frac{1}{2}(x)(6) \\
&= 3x
\end{align*}

Since both expressions for the area of the triangle are equal, we have:

$$\frac{1}{2}x^2 = 3x$$

Multiplying both sides by $2$ and dividing both sides by $x$ (since $x$ cannot be $0$), we have:

$$x = 6$$

Therefore, the area of the triangle is:

\begin{align*}
\text{Area of triangle} &= \frac{1}{2}(x)(x) \\
&= \frac{1}{2}(6)(6) \\
&= \boxed{18}
\end{align*}

