We can start by graphing $f(x)$ for some values of $p$ to get an idea of what's going on. Let's start with $p=5$:

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

real f(real x) {
  return(abs(x - 5) + abs(x - 15) + abs(x - 10));
}

draw(graph(f,-1,16),red);
draw((5,0)--(5,f(5)),dashed);
draw((10,0)--(10,f(10)),dashed);
draw((15,0)--(15,f(15)),dashed);

label("$p = 5$",(8,-10),red);
[/asy]

We can see that $f(x)$ is piecewise linear, with "breakpoints" at $x=p,$ $x=10,$ and $x=15.$ We can break up the interval $p \leq x \leq 15$ into three subintervals: $p \leq x \leq 10,$ $10 \leq x \leq 15,$ and $x=p$ (which is just a single point). On each of these subintervals, $f(x)$ is linear, so it attains its minimum at one of the endpoints.

On the interval $p \leq x \leq 10,$ we have $f(x) = (x-p) + (15-x) + (x-p-15) = 2x - 2p,$ so the minimum value is attained at $x=p,$ and is equal to $2p - 2p = 0.$

On the interval $10 \leq x \leq 15,$ we have $f(x) = (x-p) + (x-15) + (p-15) = 2x - 2p,$ so the minimum value is attained at $x=15,$ and is equal to $2 \cdot 15 - 2p = 30 - 2p.$

Finally, at $x=p,$ we have $f(p) = (p-p) + (15-p) + (p-15) = 2(15-p),$ so the minimum value is attained at $x=p,$ and is equal to $2(15-p).$

Putting it all together, we see that the minimum value of $f(x)$ on the interval $p \leq x \leq 15$ is $\boxed{2(15-p)}.$

