\begin{align*}
\cos 120^\circ &= \cos (120^\circ - 360^\circ) \\
&= \cos (-240^\circ)
\end{align*}

Now, we know that $\cos$ is an even function, meaning that $\cos (-x) = \cos x$ for all $x$. Therefore, we have:

\begin{align*}
\cos (-240^\circ) &= \cos (240^\circ) \\
&= \cos (360^\circ - 120^\circ) \\
&= \cos 240^\circ
\end{align*}

Finally, we note that $\cos$ is a periodic function with period $360^\circ$, so $\cos x = \cos (x + 360^\circ)$ for all $x$. Therefore, we can add or subtract multiples of $360^\circ$ to the argument of $\cos$ without changing its value. In particular, we can add $360^\circ$ to $240^\circ$ until we get an angle between $0^\circ$ and $360^\circ$. We have:

\begin{align*}
\cos 240^\circ &= \cos (240^\circ + 360^\circ) \\
&= \cos 600^\circ
\end{align*}

Now, we note that $\cos$ is a periodic function with period $360^\circ$, so $\cos x = \cos (x + 360^\circ)$ for all $x$. Therefore, we can subtract multiples of $360^\circ$ from $600^\circ$ until we get an angle between $0^\circ$ and $360^\circ$. We have:

\begin{align*}
\cos 600^\circ &= \cos (600^\circ - 360^\circ) \\
