We can start by computing $p(n+1)$. We have:

\begin{align*}
p(n+1) &= (n+1)^2 - (n+1) + 41 \\
&= n^2 + 2n + 1 - n - 1 + 41 \\
&= n^2 + n + 41.
\end{align*}

Now we want to find the smallest positive integer $n$ such that $\gcd(p(n), p(n+1)) > 1$. In other words, we want to find the smallest $n$ such that $p(n)$ and $p(n+1)$ share a common factor other than $1$.

If $\gcd(p(n), p(n+1)) > 1$, then this common factor must divide the difference $p(n+1) - p(n)$. We have:

\begin{align*}
p(n+1) - p(n) &= (n^2 + n + 41) - (n^2 - n + 41) \\
&= 2n.
\end{align*}

Therefore, if $\gcd(p(n), p(n+1)) > 1$, then the common factor must divide $2n$. But $p(n)$ is odd for all positive integers $n$, so the common factor cannot be $2$. Therefore, the common factor must be an odd prime.

We know that $p(n)$ is prime for many small positive integer values of $n$. In fact, $p(n)$ is prime for all $0 \leq n \leq 39$. We can check this by computing $p(n)$ for each of these values and verifying that it is prime. Therefore, if $\gcd(p(n), p(n+1)) > 1$, then the common factor must be one of the primes $p(0), p(1), \ldots, p(39)$.

We can check each of these primes in turn by computing $p(n)$ and $p(n+1)$ for $0 \leq n \leq 39$ and checking if they share the prime as a common factor. The first prime that works is $p(10) = 10^2 - 10 + 41 = 131$. We have:

\begin{align*}
\gcd(p(10), p(11)) &= \gcd(131, 151) \\
&= 1.
\end{align*}

Therefore, $p(10)$ and $p(11)$ do not share a common factor other than $1$. The next prime to try is $p(11) = 11^2 - 11 + 41 = 151$. We have:

\begin{align*}
\gcd(p(11), p(12)) &= \gcd(151, 173) \\
&= 1.
\end{align*}

Therefore, $p(11)$ and $p(12)$ do not share a common factor other than $1$. Continuing in this way, we find that the first pair of consecutive values of $n$ for which $p(n)$ and $p(n+1)$ share a common factor greater than $1$ is $n = \boxed{40}$. We have:

\begin{align*}
\gcd(p(40), p(41)) &= \gcd(40^2 - 40 + 41, 41^2 - 41 + 41) \\
&= \gcd(1681, 1681) \\
&= 1681.
\end{align*}

