Let $a = re^{i \theta}$ and $b = re^{i \phi}.$ Then $a + b = re^{i \theta} + re^{i \phi} = r(e^{i \theta} + e^{i \phi}).$ Since $|a + b| = r,$ $e^{i \theta}$ and $e^{i \phi}$ are the roots of
\[z^2 + z + 1 = 0.\]Then $e^{i \theta}$ and $e^{i \phi}$ are the cube roots of unity, so they are $1,$ $e^{2 \pi i/3},$ and $e^{4 \pi i/3}.$

If $e^{i \theta} = 1$ and $e^{i \phi} = 1,$ then $a = b,$ so $\frac{a}{b} = 1.$

If $e^{i \theta} = e^{2 \pi i/3}$ and $e^{i \phi} = e^{4 \pi i/3},$ then
\[\frac{a}{b} = \frac{re^{2 \pi i/3}}{re^{4 \pi i/3}} = e^{2 \pi i/3} \cdot e^{-4 \pi i/3} = e^{-2 \pi i/3} = \frac{1}{2} - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} i.\]

If $e^{i \theta} = e^{4 \pi i/3}$ and $e^{i \phi} = e^{2 \pi i/3},$ then
\[\frac{a}{b} = \frac{re^{4 \pi i/3}}{re^{2 \pi i/3}} = e^{4 \pi i/3} \cdot e^{-2 \pi i/3} = e^{2 \pi i/3} = \frac{1}{2} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} i.\]

Therefore, the sum of all possible values of $\frac{a}{b}$ is
\[1 + \left( \frac{1}{2} - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} i \right) + \left( \frac{1}{2} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} i \right) = \boxed{2}.\]

