Now, we can use the Law of Cosines on $\triangle ABD$ to find $\cos \angle BAD.$

\begin{align*}
\cos \angle BAD &= \frac{AB^2 + BD^2 - AD^2}{2 \cdot AB \cdot BD} \\
&= \frac{6^2 + \left(\frac{48}{17}\right)^2 - AD^2}{2 \cdot 6 \cdot \frac{48}{17}} \\
&= \frac{289}{408} - \frac{AD^2}{144}.
\end{align*}

Similarly, we can use the Law of Cosines on $\triangle ACD$ to find $\cos \angle CAD.$

\begin{align*}
\cos \angle CAD &= \frac{AC^2 + CD^2 - AD^2}{2 \cdot AC \cdot CD} \\
&= \frac{10^2 + \left(\frac{64}{17}\right)^2 - AD^2}{2 \cdot 10 \cdot \frac{64}{17}} \\
&= \frac{289}{680} - \frac{AD^2}{100}.
\end{align*}

Since $\angle BAD$ and $\angle CAD$ are supplementary, we have $\cos \angle BAD = -\cos \angle CAD.$ Therefore,

\[\frac{289}{408} - \frac{AD^2}{144} = -\left(\frac{289}{680} - \frac{AD^2}{100}\right).\]

Solving for $AD^2,$ we find $AD^2 = \boxed{\frac{3600}{17}}.$

